ars as Olympic take the lead in title race] Illawarra Mercury</ref> as well in a 3-0 trouncing of [[Albion Park White Eagles]]<ref>[http://websites.sportstg.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=1-4704-0-0-0&sID=352503&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=57862050 UEDA STRIKES GOLD FOR OLYMPIC] Football South Coast - SportsTG</ref> during 2017, also producing a brace to overpower [[Cringila Lions FC|Cringila Lions]] 2-0 on the 28th of April 2018.<ref>[http://websites.sportstg.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=0-4704-0-0-0&sID=352503&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=61996268 UEDA DOUBLE DOWNS CRINGILA] Football South Coast - SportsTG</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/5383538/ueda-inspires-olympic-success/ Ueda inspires Olympic success] \n* [https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/\u4e0a\u7530\u7950\u8f14 Japanese wikipedia Page] \n* [http://www.footballsouthcoast.com/team_info.cgi?action=PSTATS&pID=201355608&client=0-4704-62817-401227-14753897 SportsTG Profile] \n* [https://gh.soccerway.com/players/yusuke-ueda/331125/ at Soccerway]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ueda, Yusuke}}\n[[Category:Association football people from Shizuoka Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in Australia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Albirex Niigata Singapore FC players]]\n[[Category:Singapore Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Kibi International University alumni]]\n[[Category:SP Kyoto FC players]]\n[[Category:Japanese footballers]]\n\n\n{{Japan-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yusuke_Ueda"}
{"title_page": "Lo Mang", "text_new": "{{infobox person\n| name = Lo Mang\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Lo Hin Lam\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1952|7|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Hong Kong]]\n| occupation = [[actor]], [[comedian]], [[martial artist]] ho\u1ea1t \u0111\u1ed9ng 1976 - nay\n| module = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n| t = \u7f85\u83bd\n| s = \u7f57\u83bd\n| p = luo2 mang3\n}}\n| module2 = {{infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| alias = Johnson Law<br />Turbo Law<br />Ramone Law<br />Ramon Lo<br />Law Mong\n | background = temporary\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Lo Mang''' is a [[Hong Kong]] based veteran martial artist who was born as '''Lo Hin Lam''' in Hong Kong on 23 July 1952.<ref>[http://www.teako170.com/lomang.html Shaw Brother's legend Lo Mang visits Philadelphia - August 2007]</ref> Primarily known for starring in ''[[Shaw Brothers]]'' kung fu movies during the latter part of the 1970s and into the 1980s. He is a member of the famous ensemble known as the ''[[Venom Mob]]'' who were renowned for their martial arts and acting skills.\n\nHis most famous roles are '''the Toad, #5''' in Chang Cheh's ''[[The Five Deadly Venoms]]''  and '''Golden Arm Kid''' in ''[[Kid with the Golden Arm]]''. He is a skilled martial artist and practiced [[Taijiquan]] for years, as well as Chu Gar Tong Long [[Southern Praying Mantis]] for over 13 years before starting an acting career. He had a well built physique despite doing no weight training. Sometimes referred as \"Shaolin Hercules,\" he is renowned for playing the strongest personality in the movies but being the first one to be killed.\n\nHe is still active in the Hong Kong TV industry. Nowadays he has revamped his acting style as a comedy actor and is involved in directing action choreography for some productions.\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Expand list|date=February 2011}}\n*''[[Shaolin Temple (1976 film)|Shaolin Temple]]'' (1976) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Death Chamber'' - Shaolin monk\n*''[[The Naval Commandos]]'' (1977)\n*''[[The Last Strike]]'' (1977) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Soul Brothers Of Kung Fu''\n*''[[Chinatown Kid]]'' (1977) - Green Drangons gang leader\n*''[[The Brave Archer]]'' (1977) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Kung Fu Warlords'' - Han Pao Chu of the Seven Weirdos of Chiang-Nan\n*''[[The Brave Archer 2]]'' (1978) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Kung Fu Warlords Part II'' - Iron Palm Chief\n*''[[Five Deadly Venoms]]'' (1978) - Li Hao the Toad (#5)\n*''[[Invincible Shaolin]]'' (1978)  a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Unbeatable Dragon'' - Ho Ming Pao\n*''[[Kid With The Golden Arm]]'' (1979) - Golden Arm, Chief #1 of the Chih Sah Gang\n*''[[Crippled Avengers]]'' (1979) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Mortal Combat''; a.k.a. ''[[Dragon Dynasty]]'' region 1 DVD title: ''[[Return of the 5 Deadly Venoms]]'' - the deaf & mute blacksmith Wei\n*''[[Shaolin Rescuers]]'' (1979) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Avenging Warriors Of Shaolin'' - Chin Ah Chen\n*''[[Magnificent Ruffians]]'' (1979) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''The Destroyers'' - Kuan Yun\n*''[[The Daredevils]]'' (1979) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Daredevils Of Kung Fu'' - Yang Ta-Ying\n*''[[Life Gamble]]'' (1979) (shot in 1977) - Mo Chun-Feng\n*''[[Heaven and Hell (film)|Heaven and Hell]]'' (1980) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Shaolin Hellgate'' (shot in 1976) - Wei Han Ting \n*''[[The Rebel Intruders]]'' (1980) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Killer Army'' - Chi Chun-Peng\n*''[[2 Champions Of Shaolin]]'' (1980) - Tong Chien-Chin \"the Shaolin Hercules\"\n*''[[Ten Tigers of Kwangtung]]'' (1979) - Iron Fingers Chen Tie Fou\n*''[[The Brave Archer 3]]'' (1981) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Blast Of The Iron Palm'' - Iron Palm Chief\n*''[[Lion Vs. Lion]]'' (1981) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Roar Of The Lion'' - Ah Yu\n*''[[Battle for the Republic of China]]'' (1981)\n*''[[Clan Feuds]] (1982) aka: The Great Banner - Yun Cheng\n*''[[Five Element Ninjas]]'' (1982) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Super Ninjas'' - Liang Chi-Sheng\n*''[[Human Lanterns]]'' (1982) - Kuei Sze-Yin\n*''[[Hex After Hex]]'' (1982) - Tsang Ma Su\n*''[[82 Tenants]]'' (1982) - Johnny Lo\n*''[[Bastard Swordsman]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Fast Fingers]]'' (1983) - Captain Tieh Li Wei\n*''[[Men from the Gutter]] (1983) - Sgt. Chao\n*''[[Secret Service of the Imperial Court]]'' (1984) - Chao Pu Kuan\n*''[[Crazy Shaolin Disciples]]'' (1985) a.k.a. U.S. VHS title: ''Enter The 36th Chamber'' - Hung Hsi-Kuan\n*''[[Pursuit of a Killer]]'' (1985) - Ye Hong\n*''[[This Man Is Dangerous]]'' (1985) - Chief Inspector Luo\n*''[[Naughty Boys]]'' (1986)\n*''[[Hard Boiled]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Sex and Zen III]]'' (1998)\n*''[[Fire of Conscience]]'' (2010) - Tram witness\n*''[[Ip Man 2]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Gallants (film)|Gallants]]'' (2010) - Qilin\n*''[[Beach Spike]]'' (2011)\n*''[[The Grandmaster (film)|The Grandmaster]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Ip Man 3]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Buddy Cops]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Vampire Cleanup Department]]'' (2017)\n*''[https://madeinchinatownmovie.com/ Made in Chinatown]'' (2019)\n*[[Ip Man 4]] (2019)\n\n===Television series===\n* ''[[Mystery of the Twin Swords II]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[The Buddhism Palm Strikes Back]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Condor Heroes Return]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Romance of the White Hair Maiden (1995 TV series)|The Romance of the White Hair Maiden]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Journey to the West II]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Witness to a Prosecution]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[The Heaven Sword and Dragon Saber (2000 TV series)|The Heaven Sword and Dragon Saber]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Word Twisters' Adventures]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[The Seventh Day (TV series)|The Seventh Day]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[A Journey Called Life]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[D.I.E.]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Catch Me Now]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[You're Hired (TV series)|You're Hired]]'' (2009) - Employee of debt collector's company\n* ''[[The Season of Fate]]'' (2010) - Shing-tin's bodyguard\n* ''[[My Better Half (TV series)|My Better Half]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[In the Eye of the Beholder]]'' (2010) - Cameo ep. 10\n* ''[[Fly with Me (TV series)|Fly with Me]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[The Mysteries of Love]]'' (2010) - Guest star ep. 11\n* ''[[Grace Under Fire (2011 TV series)|Grace Under Fire]]'' (2011) - Guest star ep. 1, 21 - 22\n* ''[[L'Escargot (TV series)|L'Escargot]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Til Love Do Us Lie]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Three Kingdoms RPG]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Divas in Distress]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Silver Spoon, Sterling Shackles]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Inbound Troubles]]'' (2013) ep. 4 and 16\n* ''[[Come Home Love]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[A Change of Heart (TV series)|A Change of Heart]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Always and Ever]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Queen Divas]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Line Walker]]'' (2014) ep. 17, 18, 25 and 26 \n* ''[[Raising the Bar (2015 TV series)|Raising the Bar]]'' (2015) - Sit Kim  \n* ''[[Blue Veins (TV series)|Blue Veins]]'' (2016) - Chan Tai-ping\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.teako170.com/lomang2.html Lo Mang visits US/ 2007]\n* {{IMDb name|0516327|Meng Lo}}\n* {{hkmdb name|4391|Lo Meng}}\n* [http://www.hkcinemagic.com/en/people.asp?id=673 Lo Meng] at the [[Hong Kong Cinemagic]]\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lo, Mang}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong martial artists]]\n[[Category:TVB veteran actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong people of Hakka descent]]\n[[Category:Indigenous inhabitants of the New Territories in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:People from Huiyang]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox person\n| name = Lo Mang\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Lo Hin Lam\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1952|7|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Hong Kong]]\n| occupation = [[actor]], [[comedian]], [[martial artist]] ho\u1ea1t \u0111\u1ed9ng 1976 - nay\n| module = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n| t = \u7f85\u83bd\n| s = \u7f57\u83bd\n| p = luo2 mang3\n}}\n| module2 = {{infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| alias = Johnson Law<br />Turbo Law<br />Ramone Law<br />Ramon Lo<br />Law Mong\n | background = temporary\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Lo Mang''' is a [[Hong Kong]] based veteran martial artist who was born as '''Lo Hin Lam''' in Hong Kong on 23 July 1952.<ref>[http://www.teako170.com/lomang.html Shaw Brother's legend Lo Mang visits Philadelphia - August 2007]</ref> Primarily known for starring in ''[[Shaw Brothers]]'' kung fu movies during the latter part of the 1970s and into the 1980s. He is a member of the famous ensemble known as the ''[[Venom Mob]]'' who were renowned for their martial arts and acting skills.\n\nHis most famous roles are '''the Toad, #5''' in Chang Cheh's ''[[The Five Deadly Venoms]]''  and '''Golden Arm Kid''' in ''[[Kid with the Golden Arm]]''. He is a skilled martial artist and practiced [[Taijiquan]] for years, as well as Chu Gar Tong Long [[Southern Praying Mantis]] for over 13 years before starting an acting career. He had a well built physique despite doing no weight training. Sometimes referred as \"Shaolin Hercules,\" he is renowned for playing the strongest personality in the movies but being the first one to be killed.\n\nHe is still active in the Hong Kong TV industry. Nowadays he has revamped his acting style as a comedy actor and is involved in directing action choreography for some productions.\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Expand list|date=February 2011}}\n*''[[Shaolin Temple (1976 film)|Shaolin Temple]]'' (1976) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Death Chamber'' - Shaolin monk\n*''[[The Naval Commandos]]'' (1977)\n*''[[The Last Strike]]'' (1977) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Soul Brothers Of Kung Fu''\n*''[[Chinatown Kid]]'' (1977) - Green Drangons gang leader\n*''[[The Brave Archer]]'' (1977) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Kung Fu Warlords'' - Han Pao Chu of the Seven Weirdos of Chiang-Nan\n*''[[The Brave Archer 2]]'' (1978) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Kung Fu Warlords Part II'' - Iron Palm Chief\n*''[[Five Deadly Venoms]]'' (1978) - Li Hao the Toad (#5)\n*''[[Invincible Shaolin]]'' (1978)  a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Unbeatable Dragon'' - Ho Ming Pao\n*''[[Kid With The Golden Arm]]'' (1978) - Golden Arm, Chief #1 of the Chih Sah Gang\n*''[[Crippled Avengers]]'' (1979) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Mortal Combat''; a.k.a. ''[[Dragon Dynasty]]'' region 1 DVD title: ''[[Return of the 5 Deadly Venoms]]'' - the deaf & mute blacksmith Wei\n*''[[Shaolin Rescuers]]'' (1979) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Avenging Warriors Of Shaolin'' - Chin Ah Chen\n*''[[Magnificent Ruffians]]'' (1979) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''The Destroyers'' - Kuan Yun\n*''[[The Daredevils]]'' (1979) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Daredevils Of Kung Fu'' - Yang Ta-Ying\n*''[[Life Gamble]]'' (1979) (shot in 1977) - Mo Chun-Feng\n*''[[Heaven and Hell (film)|Heaven and Hell]]'' (1980) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Shaolin Hellgate'' (shot in 1976) - Wei Han Ting \n*''[[The Rebel Intruders]]'' (1980) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Killer Army'' - Chi Chun-Peng\n*''[[2 Champions Of Shaolin]]'' (1980) - Tong Chien-Chin \"the Shaolin Hercules\"\n*''[[Ten Tigers of Kwangtung]]'' (1979) - Iron Fingers Chen Tie Fou\n*''[[The Brave Archer 3]]'' (1981) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Blast Of The Iron Palm'' - Iron Palm Chief\n*''[[Lion Vs. Lion]]'' (1981) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Roar Of The Lion'' - Ah Yu\n*''[[Battle for the Republic of China]]'' (1981)\n*''[[Clan Feuds]] (1982) aka: The Great Banner - Yun Cheng\n*''[[Five Element Ninjas]]'' (1982) a.k.a. U.S. title: ''Super Ninjas'' - Liang Chi-Sheng\n*''[[Human Lanterns]]'' (1982) - Kuei Sze-Yin\n*''[[Hex After Hex]]'' (1982) - Tsang Ma Su\n*''[[82 Tenants]]'' (1982) - Johnny Lo\n*''[[Bastard Swordsman]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Fast Fingers]]'' (1983) - Captain Tieh Li Wei\n*''[[Men from the Gutter]] (1983) - Sgt. Chao\n*''[[Secret Service of the Imperial Court]]'' (1984) - Chao Pu Kuan\n*''[[Crazy Shaolin Disciples]]'' (1985) a.k.a. U.S. VHS title: ''Enter The 36th Chamber'' - Hung Hsi-Kuan\n*''[[Pursuit of a Killer]]'' (1985) - Ye Hong\n*''[[This Man Is Dangerous]]'' (1985) - Chief Inspector Luo\n*''[[Naughty Boys]]'' (1986)\n*''[[Hard Boiled]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Sex and Zen III]]'' (1998)\n*''[[Fire of Conscience]]'' (2010) - Tram witness\n*''[[Ip Man 2]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Gallants (film)|Gallants]]'' (2010) - Qilin\n